<!--PageTitleFmt-->
        <div id='wikititle'>
          <div class='pagegroup'><a href='http://wiki.simplelog.net/Themes'>Themes</a> /</div>
          <h1 class='pagetitle'>CreateANewTheme</h1></div>
<!--PageText-->
<div id='wikitext'>
<div class='box left' >
<p><strong>Note:</strong> When <span class='wikiword'>SimpleLog</span> is in <em>development mode</em>, themes aren't cached and your site will load slower. Once you finish your theme and change your application to <em>production mode</em>, the theme will be cached and everything will be much faster. It's important to make sure you develop your theme in development mode and that your live site is running in production mode. <a class='wikilink' href='../Trouble/CommonProblems#modes'>Need help?</a>
</p></div>
<p class='vspace'>It's simple. Make a copy the themes/simplelog directory and rename it to your linking. For this example, we'll call it "simpy." Go into the simpy directory and you'll see the <a class='wikilink' href='DefaultFileStructure'>default file structure</a>. In addition, you'll find a file called FILE_DESCRIPTIONS in each view directory and subdirectory. These files tell you what each view file does, so read them when creating your theme.
</p>
<p class='vspace'>Once you've got a theme directory, the rest is easy as pie:
</p>
<div class='vspace'></div><ol><li>Change about.markdown and author.markdown appropriately. Note that the author.markdown file should only contain your name (first line) and your website (optional, second line)
<div class='vspace'></div></li><li>Go to town editing the views, javascript and CSS files (see available <a class='wikilink' href='Helpers'>helper methods</a> and <a class='wikilink' href='Preferences'>preferences</a> for use in your theme)
<div class='vspace'></div></li><li>Open <span class='wikiword'>SimpleLog</span> and go to preferences. Choose your theme from the list in the Display section
<div class='vspace'></div></li><li>Save your preferences
</li></ol><p class='vspace'>That's it, you're running your theme!
</p>
</div>

      </td>
    </tr></table>
